<br>
ae groups are great. some of the best times i have had playing the class have been spent trashing charsis. i dont think its a very practical solution to people complaining about trying to find a group. i have never participated in or even heard of a pickup ae group on my server. every time it was planned in advance and like like pretty much every other group depends on having the 2 most sought out classes to form it around. the only times i have seen enchanters and clerics unable to find a group is when for some reason there are far too many on or that particular person has a horrendous reputation. i know many enchanters that are on anon not to keep from getting requests for clarity but to reduce the number of random invitations for groups. <br>
<br>
well i seem to have wandered a bit but basically my point is yes i agree that wizards have more options than most classes but i dont agree that you are giving a true solution. personally i avoid pickup groups/raids like the plague and try to organize things with friends ahead of time. honestly that is the best way to get a group and to really enjoy the game. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ulimdul.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LimDul</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Evoker</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/15/01 2:36:23 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.lava.net/~toasty/pictures/limdul.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: This board always crack me up...</span><hr size=1> I'm my eye, it comes down to this: Verant did not do a good job defining their vision of &quot;balance&quot;; right now it seems no more then the idea that the numbers look the same at the end of a battle.<br>
<br>
The only thing I've heard them claim is that EQ is was to be designed as a group game (forget the solo game for this discussion).  Under that assumption, balance is a very subjective idea based on what people perceptions of what each class can bring to the table.  All else being equal (guild memberships, friends, MoBs, etc) we all know that there are some classes more popular then others.  <br>
<br>
So if you use the &quot;group game&quot; as a litmus test (as Verant has asked us to do so many times before)...wizards and a number of other overlooked classes will continue to be unbalanced until our abilities are more clearly defined and emphasized; be it damage output or otherwise.<br>
<br>
As much as I like the new gifts that VI gave us in the form of Translocates and Banes...I don't think it falls in the category of making us any more group oriented; at least not to the same degree as a melee damage dealer or a healer.  I think these spells may make our life easier and possibly more fun, but I have a hard time seeing any correlation with the group game vision.<br>
<br>
So the questions should simply be...ignoring any rules of damage caps and such, what would it take to make us as equally attractive as a cleric, rogue, or enchanter?  That's why many people will continue to post here with their frustrations because VI continues to cloud this question with other issues....<br>
<br>
-- Lim'Dul<br>
